# Context Engineering Guidelines

A comprehensive guide to optimizing system prompts and tool descriptions for LLM agents, synthesized from 30+ sources published since July 2025.

**Key Sources**:
- [Anthropic: Effective Context Engineering for AI Agents](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents) (Sep 2025)
- [Mei et al.: A Survey of Context Engineering for LLMs](https://huggingface.co/papers/2507.13334) (Jul 2025)
- [Jiang & Nam: Empirical Study on Developer-Provided Context](https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.18925) (Dec 2025)
- [Gartner: Context Engineering as Strategic Priority](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering) (Oct 2025)
- [InfoWorld: Four Important Lessons About Context Engineering](https://www.infoworld.com/article/4085355/four-important-lessons-about-context-engineering.html) (Jan 2026)

---

## Part 1: Foundational Principles

### The Core Thesis

Context engineering is a formal discipline that systematically optimizes information payloads for LLMs, extending far beyond prompt design to encompass the entire informational environment (Mei et al., 2025).

**Goal**: Find the *smallest possible set of high-signal tokens* that maximize desired outcomes (Anthropic, 2025).

### Why Context is Finite

LLMs have an "attention budget" constrained by transformer architecture:
- **n² pairwise relationships** for n tokens causes performance degradation at scale
- **Context rot**: As token count increases, recall accuracy decreases
- Models develop attention patterns from training where shorter sequences are more common

Every token competes for attention. Tokens that don't directly contribute to the task dilute the model's focus.

### The Context Engineering Taxonomy (Mei et al., 2025)

Context engineering decomposes into three foundational components:

| Component | Description | Examples |
|-----------|-------------|----------|
| **Context Retrieval & Generation** | Designing and assembling input payloads | Prompt construction, RAG, tool outputs |
| **Context Processing** | Transforming context into optimized representations | Summarization, chunking, compression |
| **Context Management** | Storing, persisting, and refreshing context | Memory systems, caching, compaction |

These integrate into system implementations: RAG, memory systems, tool-integrated reasoning, and multi-agent architectures.

### Developer-Provided Context Taxonomy (Jiang & Nam, 2025)

An empirical study of 401 open-source repositories with cursor rules identified five essential context categories:

1. **Conventions**: Coding style, naming patterns, formatting rules
2. **Guidelines**: Decision-making heuristics, workflow patterns
3. **Project Information**: Architecture, dependencies, domain knowledge
4. **LLM Directives**: Behavioral instructions, output format requirements
5. **Examples**: Canonical code samples, input/output demonstrations

**Insight**: Structure developer-provided context into these categories for maximum clarity.

